starting point for rethinking what students—and teachers—do. What if a teacher built a semester’s worth of teaching and learning backward—starting from what students need to learn to do by the end of the term, and only then selecting and arranging the material students need to study?Thinking through the lived moments of classroom engagement—what the authors call “coursetime”—becomes a way of striking a balance between improv and order. With fresh insights and concrete suggestions, Syllabus shifts the focus away from the teacher to the work and growth of students, moving the classroom closer to the genuinely collaborative learning community we all want to create.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCollege teaching. 0aCurriculum planning. 0aEducation, HigherxCurricula. 0aEducation, Higher-Curricula. 7aEDUCATION / Teaching Methods & Materials / General.2bisacsh  aA Thief of Time.  aAcademic integrity.  aAcademic tenure.  aAcademic term.  aAccreditation.  aActive learning.  aAdage.  aAmbiguity.  aAnecdote.  aApprenticeship.  aArchivist.  aAttendance.  aBody of knowledge.  aCalculation.  aCareer.  aCase study.  aClass size.  aClassroom.  aCoaching.  aCounting.  aCoursework.  aCritical pedagogy.  aCritical thinking.  aCurriculum.  aData science.  aDesign.  aEducational aims and objectives.  aEducational technology.  aEffectiveness.  aFaculty (academic staff).  aFaculty (division).  aFad diet.  aFamily Educational Rights and Privacy Act.  aFine-tuning.  aGenerosity.  aGrading (education).  aGraduate school.  aGroup work.  aGroupthink.  aHarvard University Press.  aHigher education.  aHomework.  aImprovisation.  aInstitution.  aIteration.  aJohn Dewey.  aLearning community.  aLearning.  aLecture.  aLesson plan.  aLiberal